only shows that if you change the fields of an object the hashcode for that object changes.

Specifically it cannot show that the hashcode from `service1` is different from the hashcode of `service2` (hint: they are not because **there is only one object**) because you change that object between the two calls and that just shows that the hashcode changes if the object changes.

To show that the hashcode for `service1` is different from the hashcode for `service2` **you must print** both hashcodes before changing the object (and you may want to print both hashcodes after changing the object):

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        log.info(&quot;hashcode before changing the object&quot;);
        log.info(&quot;service1 hashcode &quot; + service1.hashCode());
        log.info(&quot;service2 hashcode &quot; + service2.hashCode());
        log.info(&quot;changing the object&quot;);
        service1.setAmount(100L);
        service1.setPaymentStatus(&quot;success&quot;);
        log.info(&quot;hashcode after changing the object&quot;);
        log.info(&quot;service1 hashcode &quot; + service1.hashCode());
        log.info(&quot;service2 hashcode &quot; + service2.hashCode());
    }

---

&gt; _When I use the @EqualsAndHashCode annotation top of the class, service1 and service2 hashcode values are output differently._

Yes, with your sample code the hashcode values are output differently - because between those two output **you modified the object by changing fields** and changing the fields leads to a different hashcode value.

But this is not because Lomboks `@EqualsAndHashCode` is broken - it is because your sample code (especially the part where you want to show that the hashcode changes) is broken.

